SENATE CONCURRENT RESOLUTION—Recognizing the “Fruit Loop” as a
historical LGBTQ+ landmark in Clark County, Nevada.
1 WHEREAS, The State of Nevada consists of various diverse communities,
2 including, without limitation, the LGBTQ+ community, which have made
3 significant cultural, civic, economic and political contributions to the State; and
4 WHEREAS, The area where East Naples Drive meets South Paradise Road and
5 South University Center Drive in Las Vegas, Nevada, is commonly known as the
6 “Fruit Loop;” and
7 WHEREAS, Since the 1950s, numerous LGBTQ+ businesses, entertainment
8 venues and gathering spaces located in the Fruit Loop have served the LGBTQ+
9 community as a culturally and historically significant hub for activism, community-
10 building, celebrations, pride events and fundraisers; and
11 WHEREAS, The Fruit Loop has provided a safe space for the LGBTQ+
12 community for self-expression, socialization and advocacy and has contributed to
13 the diverse social, cultural and economic vitality of Las Vegas, Nevada, by
14 fostering inclusivity, acceptance, understanding and respect; and
15 WHEREAS, Recognizing historical LGBTQ+ landmarks is essential to
16 understanding the struggles, resilience and triumphs of the LGBTQ+ community;
17 now, therefore, be it
18 RESOLVED BY THE SENATE OF THE STATE OF NEVADA, THE ASSEMBLY
19 CONCURRING, That the members of the 83rd Session of the Nevada Legislature
20 hereby recognize the Fruit Loop as a historical LGBTQ+ landmark; and be it
21 further
22 RESOLVED, That the recognition of the Fruit Loop as a historical LGBTQ+
23 landmark will encourage continued support for the preservation of its legacy and
24 the promotion of LGBTQ+ history in Nevada; and be it further
25 RESOLVED, That the members of the 83rd Session of the Nevada Legislature
26 hereby urge the Director of the Department of Transportation to install directional

